China's food safety situation is concerning, with potential negative impacts on public health and the economy.
Tainted food affects millions annually, prompting government efforts to improve supervision.
Recent incidents, like food poisoning outbreaks, highlight the need for stricter regulations and accountability.
Calls for a unified supervision mechanism and harsher penalties for safety violations have been made.
The Health Ministry is working on strengthening coordination and information sharing among provinces.
A comprehensive plan to track and trace food products is expected to address recurring safety issues.
The goal is to enhance monitoring and enforcement to prevent future safety accidents.
